<!-- **********************************************************************

Course:    Intermediate Algebra/Algebra I
Chapter:   1. Linear Equations
Section:   1. What is a solution?
Author:    Anurag Katyal, Summer 2023
Contact:   katyala@palmbeachstate.edu

I'd love feedback on the activity or suggestions for improving the activity. 

About the activity: Students often learn to solve various equations in Algebra courses without necessarily knowing what they are finding or what it means for some mathematical object to be a solution. The goal of this activity is to develop students' understanding of solutions in a mathematical setting by having them check potential solutions in linear equations and inequalities. All the problems, through hopefully a happy coincidence, are previews of the remaining sections in this Chapter. 

********************************************************************** -->

<section boxed><title>What is a solution?</title>
        <video name="fitvideo" youtube="Xvr-6jIGXpw"/>
      <p>Video credit achieved: <number displayDecimals="1">$fitvideo.fractionWatched*100</number>%</p>
    
    <p>Imagine you are trying to unlock a locked door.</p>
        <ol>
          <li>A <em>solution</em> is a key that not only fits the lock but actually opens the door as well.</li>
          <li>A master key will fit and unlock any door and represents <em>all solutions</em>. </li>      
          <li>An incorrect key will not fit nor unlock the door and represents <em>no solution</em>.</li>
          <li><em>Extraneous solutions</em> are keys that fit but are missing the groves to turn the tumblers in the lock. We will see these later in the course.</li>
        </ol>

      <p>Let's take a look at the key that fits <em>and</em> opens the door as well.</p>

      <p>We say, <m>3</m> <em>is</em> a solution to <m>x+1=4</m> because if we replace <m>3</m> in for <m>x</m> in the equation, we can simplify to a <em>true statement</em>.</p>        
  
        <p>   
          <md>
            <mrow>x+1 \amp=4</mrow>
            <mrow>3+1 \amp=4</mrow>
            <mrow>4 \amp=4 ~(\checkmark~True)</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
    
      <p>However, <m>1</m> is <em>not</em> a solution to <m>x+1=4</m>, because if we replace <m>1</m> in for <m>x</m>, we can simplify to a <em>false statement</em>.</p> 
  
        <p>   
          <md>
            <mrow>x+1 \amp=4</mrow>
            <mrow>1+1 \amp=4</mrow>
            <mrow>2 \amp=4 ~(\chi~False)</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>

  <p>Next, let's look at some equations and inequalities we will cross paths with in this course.</p>


</section>

<setup><function name="p1To3Function">2x+1</function></setup>
          
<section boxed includeAutoNumber><title>Linear Equations in One Variable</title>


<!--**********************************************************************
              Problem 2.1
***********************************************************************-->

  <problem includeParentNumber>
    Is <m>4</m> a solution to <m>$p1To3Function=-4</m>?
              <answer>
                <choiceInput name="p1menu" inline>
                  <choice>Yes.</choice>
                  <choice credit="1">No. </choice>
                </choiceInput>
              </answer>
           

            
              <hint>
                If you substitute the given value into the variable, do you get a true or a false statement?
              </hint>
             
              <solution>
                
                <md>
                  <mrow>$p1To3Function=-4</mrow>
                  <mrow>2(4)+1=-4</mrow>
                  <mrow>8+1=-4</mrow>
                  <mrow>9=-4</mrow>
                  <mrow>False</mrow>
                </md>
                
                <p>
                  <m>4</m> is not a solution to <m>$p1To3Function=-4</m> because if we replace <m>4</m> in for <m>x</m>, we can simplify to a <em>false statement</em>.
                </p>
              
              </solution>
  </problem>


<!--**********************************************************************
              Problem 2.2
***********************************************************************-->
      
<problem includeParentNumber>
    Is <m>-\frac{5}{2}</m> a solution to <m>$p1To3Function=-4</m>?

           
          <p>Step 1: <nbsp/><nbsp/>
            <m>2 \bigg( </m><mathinput name="p2entry1"/><m>\bigg) + 1 = -4</m></p>

          <p>Step 2: <nbsp/><nbsp/><mathinput name="p2entry2"/><m> + 1 = -4</m></p>
              
          <p>Step 3: <nbsp/><nbsp/><mathinput name="p2entry3"/><m> = -4</m></p>

          <p>The above solution results in a              
                    <choiceInput name="tf" inline>
                      <choice>True</choice>
                      <choice>False</choice>
                    </choiceInput>
                  statement.</p>

  <answer>
            <award>
              <when>
                $p2entry1= (-5/2) and 
                $p2entry2= (-5) and 
                $p2entry3 = (-4) and 
                $tf.selectedIndex = 1
              </when>
            </award>
          </answer>
              
</problem>


